ges. Clearly presented statistical analysis shows how these characteristics interacted with poverty and welfare to influence heath and survivorship across infancy and early childhood. The book builds up sources from Foundling Hospital records, medical tracts and parish registers to illustrate how the hospital managed the care of its children, and how it reflected wider medical ideas on feeding and child health. Child fostering, paid nursing and family formation in different parts of England are also examined, showing how this metropolitan institution called on a network of contacts to try to raise its charges to good health. This book will be of considerable significance to scholars working in economic and social history, medical and institutional history and histories of childhood and childcare in the early modern period. It will also be of interest to anthropologists interested in child-rearing and feeding practices, and inter-family relationships  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFoundlingsxHealth and hygienezEnglandzLondonxHistoryy20th century. 0aFoundlingsxServices forzEnglandzLondonxHistoryy18th century. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aEngland.  aLondon Foundling Hospital.  aabandonment.  acharity.  achildcare.  aill-health.  ainfant death.  amotherhood.  anursing network.  aparish officials.  apatronage.  apoverty alleviation strategy.  asurvival prospects.  awelfare.1 aLevene, Alysa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130426423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130426/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986